The divine seal of human distinction, self, is not at such times conscious ex- cept in giving and receiving. Like this is the humility of a father lost in glad— ness over the returning runagate, or the joy of motherhood. The new-made mother cannot say in her heart to her nestling what we habitually say to others, “I am superior to you.'' She is not even conscious of her humility‚ while she looks with dread to the time when she will no longer be the menial of the tiny person. Humanity in all ages has joined in crying‚ “ Blessed are these poor in spirit, for theirs is the kingdom.”
